            "creation_date": 1349215073,
            "body": "<p>JB Nizet is right, the first steps create a DOM out of <code>xmlString<\/code>. That will load your xmlString (or SOAP message) into an in-memory Document. What the following steps are doing (all the things related with the Transform) is to serialize the DOM to a file (xmlFileName.xml), which is not what you want to do, right?<\/p>\n\n<p>When you said that your DOM is empty, I think you tried to print out the content of your DOM with <code>document.toString()<\/code>, and returned something like \"[document: null]\". This doesn't mean your DOM is empty. Actually your DOM contains data. You need now to use the DOM API to get access to the nodes inside your document. Try something like <code>document.getChildNodes(), document.getElementsByTagName(), etc<\/code><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 12698980,
            "question_id": 12698561
        }
